Copy link
I actually did this. The 32 bit version builds a ROP chain and uses a single ASM instruction to enter it. All code frames are inside kernel32.dll (now kernelbase.dll) This works because in 32 bit, all arguments are on the stack so I can just return into the entry point of the next function.
The 64 bit version however can't do that, so the asm code is allocated with VirtualAlloc and looks like this:
```
 ...Read moreI actually did this. The 32 bit version builds a ROP chain and uses a single ASM instruction to enter it. All code frames are inside kernel32.dll (now kernelbase.dll) This works because in 32 bit, all arguments are on the stack so I can just return into the entry point of the next function.
The 64 bit version however can‚Äôt do that, so the asm code is allocated with VirtualAlloc and looks like this:
‚Äú`
   push rbp
   mov rbp, rsp
   sub rsp, 32
   mov rbi, rcx
.x mov rax, [rbx]
   mov rcx, [rbx + 8]
   call rax
   add rbx, 16
   jmp short .x
‚Äú`
The problem is there‚Äôs no way to register this function for dynamic execution because the unwind is not encodable in the tables at all. (It looks like you could encode correct the stack, pop rbp, and return but you can‚Äôt because the after the fist call instruction the next stack frame is *gone*.) SInce crash the process is the right thing to do if there‚Äôs any exception thrown from `FreeLibrary`, `DeleteFile`, `RemoveDirctory`, or `ExitProcess`, it doesn‚Äôt actually matter.
As the guy said above, RemoveSelf() would have been a decent API; however I don‚Äôt _quite_ favor that route. Better would be to add IMAGE_FILE_RUN_FROM_SWAP to go with IMAGE_FILE_NET_RUN_FROM_SWAP that means always copy this binary to swap and run from there; *never* keep a lock on this binary while it‚Äôs running.
Note that the wscript version doesn‚Äôt work reliably because wscript might not be there, or the code may be running from the service desktop or something more exotic.
